    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.02892.001_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">Belmont Mass<ptr target="loc.02892_n1"/></name>
                    <date when="1885-12-02">Dec 2 '85</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>My Dear Whitman&#8212;</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Maugre <choice>
                    <abbr>yr</abbr>
                    <expan>your</expan>
                </choice> wholesome advice, (exc. that I put in a page on you &amp; Hugo&#8212;parallelism of <choice>
                    <abbr>yr</abbr>
                    <expan>your</expan>
                </choice> poetic-technique en-avant freshness &#38;c) I have done gone &amp;
                published my essay "The Poet as a Craftsman."<ptr target="loc.02599_n1"/></p>
            <p>I set up every stick of it <hi rend="underline">mesilf indade</hi>, &amp; corrected
                my proofs (<choice><abbr>wh.</abbr>
                    <expan>which</expan>
                </choice> I'll have you know) were pronounced excellent by the <hi rend="underline"
                    >other</hi> typos. You didn't know I had learned <choice>
                    <abbr>yr</abbr>
                    <expan>your</expan>
                </choice> boyhood's art, did you? Well, I have learned just enough to set up this
                &amp; my poems (Heaven bless the mark&#8212;"poems" quotha,&#8212;I <choice>
                    <abbr>wd'nt</abbr>
                    <expan>wouldn't</expan>
                </choice> have <hi rend="underline">you</hi> ever see 'em for a Scotch haggis, or a
                shining gold piece&#8212;). I <choice>
                    <abbr>pub.</abbr>
                    <expan>published</expan>
                </choice> an edition of <hi rend="underline">six</hi> copies of the poems! Of this
                monograph I struck off 300 copies. McKay (the "publisher") (lucus a non) has 225.
                You may tell him to let you have all you want at 12&#189; cts; retail price 25</p>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.02892.002_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc.02892.003_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">I do hope</hi> you are feeling well, &amp; pray fervently you
                may weather the winter very comfortably. How's the pony?</p>
            <p>I am going to send copies of "Poet as <choice>
                    <abbr>Crafts</abbr><expan>Craftsman</expan></choice>" to Bucke,<ptr target="n0119"/> Swinburne,<ptr target="n0610"/>
                    Tennyson,<ptr target="n0625"/> Rossetti,<ptr target="n0522"/> O'Connor,<ptr
                    target="n2002"/> Burroughs,<ptr target="n0129"/> Dowden (what's his
                    address?)<ptr target="n0199"/> Gilder,<ptr target="n0871"/> &amp;
                    O'Reilly.<ptr target="n4973"/> These of <choice>
                    <abbr>yr</abbr>
                    <expan>your</expan>    
                </choice> personal friends I mention so you need not send duplicates. I am sick of
                the pamphlet by this time; <hi rend="underline">but I believe in it</hi> still very
                thoroughly, &amp; hope it will elicit new thoughts &amp; better, &amp; be a
                bugle-note for reform.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>affectionately, as ever</salute>
                <signed>W. S. Kennedy</signed>
            </closer>
            <!--bottom of letter includes line doodles-->
            <postscript>
                <p>I read of the English gift of $500, with joy </p>
            </postscript>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002v" facs="loc.02892.004_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <note type="editorial" resp="#ww" place="top">I send you 3 copies.</note>
            <pb xml:id="leaf003r" facs="loc.02892.005_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
